<comment datatype='string'>&lt;i&gt;ascG&lt;/i&gt; encodes a repressor that is expressed constantly during the exponential and stationary phases, yielding about 500 to 700 molecules in the genome [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19633077&quot;&gt;Ishida09&lt;/a&gt;].
This regulator represses the cryptic operon &lt;i&gt;ascFB&lt;/i&gt; [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19633077&quot;&gt;Ishida09&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1630307&quot;&gt;Hall92a&lt;/a&gt;],but only the transcription of this operon was activated by a mutation that involved adding an insertion sequence (IS&lt;i&gt;186&lt;/i&gt;) element into &lt;i&gt;ascG&lt;/i&gt; [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1630307&quot;&gt;Hall92a&lt;/a&gt;]. Ishihama in 2009 did not observe an effect on self-regulation [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1630307&quot;&gt;Hall92a&lt;/a&gt;].
